1) First collect barks from different kinds of trees (such as oak). 2) Dry them under sunlight for few days so they can be used without getting wet again. They will dry out quickly if it’s raining outside. This step helps remove water from the wood fibers which makes it easier to use when writing on these papers.3) Grind up the dried barks into fine powder form.4) Make pulp by mixing the ground-up bark with water(add about two times more amount of water than required because once mixed together, there would still remain some residue particles.)5) Mix the pulp with other ingredients like clay and salt before adding the solution over an already prepared surface made by laying down cloth/paper sheets one upon another.6) Pressed between stones at low temperatures until all excess liquid has been absorbed.7) Then hang this new piece of fabric onto ropes hung across a beam in order to let it rest undisturbed, for several weeks - depending on the thickness of each sheet – during which time the fibres become aligned.8) The process of making paper involves applying pressure through many layers of tissue to achieve strength and uniformity; this was done manually initially but today large machines are employed to do most of the pressing work.9) Then spread thinly over smooth boards (usually birchwood), to take advantage of its superior glossiness.10) Ink should now stick to the surface better enabling printing.11) After passing through a series of rollers, sheets can be trimmed according to need.

