The main difference between these two technologies lies in their method for creating an image on screen. In Cinema Laser Projection systems, light is generated by using a gas discharge lamp (similar to those used in old TVs). This produces a very bright white light which can be modulated with RGB color filters to create images. These lamps have a much longer life than LED based projectors but they also consume more power. They produce a brighter picture at higher contrast ratios compared to LED based projector systems. However, this comes at the cost of increased heat generation within the room due to the high energy consumption of such bulbs.

Answer: \begin{blockquote}
\em{\strong{"How does a cinema laser projection system work?"}}
\end{blockquote}

The basic idea behind all types of digital movie projection is to use a series of tiny mirrors called "digital micromirror devices" (DMD) to reflect individual pixels onto a large screen. Each pixel has three colors - red, green, blue - so each one needs its own microscopic mirror. A typical DMD chip contains about 1 million of them.

<a href="https://i.stack.imgur.com/64X0Km.jpg" rel="nofollow noreferrer"><IMAGE></a>

Each time a frame changes, the computer sends out new instructions telling the DMD what to do next. It takes just milliseconds before the entire screen flickers into action.

A single DMD chip can only handle around 25 frames per second, however, so there’s usually several chips working together inside the projector.

Inside most modern cinemas, the film is stored digitally rather than physically. That means the data doesn’t need to travel through miles of wires like it did when films were shot on celluloid. Instead

