Answer: \begin{itemize}
\item The first line is not needed because it contains all tags already. We just need to remove comments and add new lines only when there are changes (increase or decrease) between two adjacent lines, otherwise we keep them together.
\item To detect if an increase or decrease from one line number to another use regex `\d+:\d+\n(\s*[A-Z]+:.*\S)\s*\r`. Here "re" modifier enables the capture group inside parenthesis (to find if tag changed), `[\w\W]` means alphanumeric characters including underscore `_`, `$` matches end of string anchor (`^$`) which is used here by replacing last character (`\z`). Also note `[A-Z]`: capital letters will match digits too. It will search in next line after every newline characater followed by whitespace (space). Finally `\r` at end makes sure that the second line has ended properly before searching again on the same input line. So now we can easily differentiate change from previous line by whether a space or nonexistent space exists.
\end{itemize}

