O(f*n^2) = f * n ^ (2 + epsilon), where epsilon is a small constant. The function grows with the input size. For example when n=10 it will grow by at least one order of magnitude compared to when n=3. It can also be expressed using asymptotic notation as follows : lim_{N -> inf } o(f * N^a)=f * a.

Answer: I would write this as "O" for Big-Oh. This means that the growth rate approaches some number \em{x} over time; but we do not care about how much slower than \em{x}.

For instance, if \strong{\em{{f}} = 1}, then the value \strong{{\strong{o}({f}*{n}^{e})} == {e}}. So let us take an arbitrary \strong{[Big Oh]}. Then, \strong{{f}*{n}^[Big Oh]} is equivalent to \strong{{f}*{n}^e} wherein [the exponent e is a variable which depends on the values of \strong{{f}}]. Thus, we can define our \strong{Big-Oh} function such way that it has the following property: \begin{code}
