I am not sure about this but i guess it can be one factor affecting performance. In my understanding , the value ranges from 0 (not used)to  1(used). It is an optional hyperparameter which determines how much importance is given when choosing between two trees with equal depth . The larger the number ,the more weight will assigned towards smaller nodes than large ones. A high value of GAMMA indicates a tree structure where each leaf node has fewer children so the decision boundary becomes steeper at lower values of features . A low gamma value results in deeper and wider trees so that there are many branches for each split. For deep learning models such as xgboost, the higher gamma means less pruning.

Answer: \begin{blockquote}
\em{Can you explain to me the parameter [gamma]?}
What is [its] impact on the model’s performance?
