I am going to assume you have already read the official documentation here: https://xgboost.readthedocs.io/en/latest/model.html

Gamma controls the trade-off between the depth and complexity of the decision tree and the speed with which predictions could be made. High values lead to very shallow decision trees; Low values result in complex decisions trees. This is useful if we want to predict fast but also get good accuracy because then we would need to use only simple decissions trees and thus reduce the time needed by using parallelism techniques like threading, multi-threading etc.. On the other hand, we may want to achieve better accuracy even though the process takes longer due to the use of complex trees. So, what we do is we set a higher value of gamma to create simpler decision tress leading us to faster processing times and viceversa.

